    investmentStrategy:"Rare convergence: established Core Services relationship + time-bounded technology adoption window created by restructuring mandate + three concurrent launch programmes. Risk: competitor technology vendors (Accenture via SAP, Veeva via RIM) could establish a foothold in the Transformation Office before Freyr converts its regulatory incumbency into a technology relationship. The 60-90 day CEO transition window (June–September 2026) is the most important timing factor.",
    strategicPriorities:[
      { priority:'URGENT', title:'H2 2026 Product Launches — oveporexton, rusfertide, zasocitinib', body:"Three simultaneous launches — oveporexton (narcolepsy type 1, Breakthrough Therapy + Fast Track, US/Japan/China NDA/MAA active), rusfertide (polycythemia vera, FDA Priority Review), and zasocitinib (psoriasis, EU/US preparation) — require regulatory operations, eCTD v4.0 readiness, labeling lifecycle, REMS compliance, and PV programme initiation simultaneously. Current in-house capacity is under pressure from the simultaneous 4,500-person restructuring.", freyrAction:"SUBMIT PRO + LABEL 360 + rDMS + Regulatory Operations — provide surge capacity for all three launches without requiring Takeda to hire FTEs that will then be in scope for restructuring. Robertson QBR is the trigger. Q3 2026.", nudgeSignal:"oveporexton FDA review H2 2026 — submission capacity scoping is a Q3 2026 emergency, not a planning item. Freyr must confirm resource allocation NOW.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"This is the most urgent and highest-revenue near-term entry point. Three simultaneous regulatory submissions during a 4,500-person restructuring creates an outsourcing mandate Freyr is uniquely positioned to fill." },
      { priority:'URGENT', title:'JPY 200B Cost Reduction / 4,500-Person Restructuring', body:"Takeda's transformation programme targets JPY 200 billion in annualised gross savings by FY2028. Restructuring expenses of approximately JPY 150B are planned for FY2026, including a 4,500-person global workforce reduction. The regulatory function's headcount is in scope for reduction. The Transformation Office under Lauren Duprey (Chief Transformation Officer, effective April 1, 2026) is the budget owner for all technology investments that deliver measurable FTE reduction.", freyrAction:"VIA (Variation Identification Agent) eliminates manual variation management lookup across 25+ manufacturing sites. freya.intelligence replaces regulatory monitoring FTEs with automated continuous intelligence. Both generate auditable FTE reduction outcomes Duprey can report to Kim. Lead with: 'How many FTEs does Takeda spend on regulatory monitoring and variation management?'", nudgeSignal:"Transformation Office building FY2027 technology portfolio NOW. The 60-90 day CEO transition window is the most important timing factor. Accenture via SAP and Veeva via RIM are competing for this budget.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"Freyr must be in the Transformation Office before the FY2027 technology portfolio closes. Miss this window and the technology vendor agenda is set without Freyr on the shortlist." },
      { priority:'HIGH', title:"GenAI Dossier Programme — Robertson's 50%+ Compilation Time Target", body:"Andrew Robertson's team co-leads a GenAI regulatory dossier prototype with a 50%+ dossier compilation time reduction target. Robertson has published (Nature Reviews Drug Discovery, 2025) the case for cloud-based federated regulatory submission platforms — the exact architecture SUBMIT PRO + freya fusion instantiates. Robertson also sits on the Weave Bio Strategic Advisory Board (inaugural member, March 2026) focused on HAQ automation.", freyrAction:"freya fusion's GenAI dossier authoring module with GxP guardrails is the production-grade platform Robertson's programme requires. Position Freyr as the operational instantiation of his published vision: 'We built the production layer of your NatRevDrugDisc architecture.' Multi-LLM with GxP guardrails maps directly to Ricci's 5-pillar responsible AI framework.", nudgeSignal:"Robertson published the federated submission platform thesis. Freyr SUBMIT PRO + freya fusion IS the thesis in production. This is a once-in-a-partnership positioning opportunity.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"Robertson is Freyr's warmest contact and the internal champion who will advocate for freya fusion to Duprey and Ricci. The GenAI dossier programme is the technical credibility entry point for the full technology track." },
      { priority:'HIGH', title:'eCTD v4.0 Readiness and Cloud Submission Platform', body:"Robertson has publicly published (NatRevDrugDisc 2025) the case for cloud-based federated regulatory submission platforms, co-authoring with The Charles Forum. PMDA Japan mandates eCTD v4.0 effective 2026 — directly affecting Takeda's Japanese filings. EMA plans mandatory v4.0 adoption by 2027. FDA accepts v4.0 from September 2024 with mandate planned for 2029. Three concurrent H2 2026 launches include Japan filings immediately affected by the PMDA v4.0 mandate.", freyrAction:"SUBMIT PRO with 800+ validation checks is the fastest route to v4.0 compliance. Position as the production-grade operational layer of Robertson's published vision. Demo to Robertson Reg Ops team in Q3 2026 QBR. Extend to rDMS cloud-native document management for Robertson's federated submission platform architecture.", nudgeSignal:"PMDA Japan v4.0 mandate is NOW — affects oveporexton Japan filings immediately. Robertson has published his vision — SUBMIT PRO is the implementation.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"eCTD v4.0 is the technical entry point that requires no new relationship investment — Robertson already owns this problem, Freyr already has the solution. This is the easiest first win in the technology track." },
      { priority:'HIGH', title:'AI/Digital Transformation — Duprey Transformation Office Mandate', body:"Lauren Duprey's Chief Transformation Officer mandate (from April 1, 2026): 'connect transformation across the company, including AI initiatives.' She controls the FY2027 enterprise AI investment portfolio. Her mandate is workforce redesign — reducing headcount dependency through AI-enabled automation. She approaches AI as a people challenge, not a technology challenge. Ricci (CDTO) is the technology gatekeeper with a 5-pillar responsible AI framework and explicit anti-pilot-itis philosophy.", freyrAction:"Lead with workforce framing, not platform architecture. Ask Duprey: 'How many FTEs does Takeda spend on regulatory monitoring and variation management?' VIA + freya.intelligence FTE reduction model with auditable outcomes is the entry narrative. For Ricci: freya fusion multi-LLM architecture maps to his multi-model orchestration philosophy. Position as production deployment, never as pilot.", nudgeSignal:"Duprey is building FY2027 technology portfolio NOW. Ricci has personally bought $500K+ of TAK stock (April 2026) — authentic institutional commitment signal. Both are approachable via Robertson.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"The Transformation Office is the budget owner. Every Freyr technology dollar goes through Duprey. Without a Duprey relationship, the technology track stalls regardless of Robertson's advocacy." },
      { priority:'MEDIUM', title:'Pharmacovigilance — Three New Commercial Products', body:"oveporexton, rusfertide, and zasocitinib each require PV programme establishment at commercial launch. Three simultaneous new molecules entering commercial phase significantly increase PV operational load. ICSR processing, PSUR/PBRER authoring, signal detection, and aggregate reporting for three assets simultaneously is a significant capacity requirement that exceeds internal headcount during restructuring.", freyrAction:"Introduce Freyr PV services in parallel with the H2 2026 launch regulatory operations conversation. Identify Head of PV Director via Robertson introduction. 'Who is managing PV for oveporexton and rusfertide?' is the opening question.", nudgeSignal:"Three simultaneous commercial launches = three new PV programmes simultaneously. Adjacent to existing RA relationship. Q3-Q4 2026 entry.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"PV is the Growth Services entry point that leverages the Robertson relationship. Position alongside the Core Services launch support conversation for a single integrated proposal." },
      { priority:'MEDIUM', title:'CMC Variation Management — 25+ Global Manufacturing Sites', body:"Takeda's manufacturing consolidation (Factory of the Future programme across 25+ global sites) generates a variation filing surge that the regulatory team may not yet have fully scoped. Post-approval change management across 25+ manufacturing sites requires ongoing CMC variation filings across multiple regulatory agencies globally. VIA's authority-specific variation recommendations directly reduce cycle time and cost per variation.", freyrAction:"Sell VIA to the Factory of the Future programme lead — not just the CMC Regulatory Director. The budget owner is the manufacturing operations programme, not the RA budget. Pitch ROI: variation cycle time reduction (X%) and cost per filing (Y%) across 25+ sites.", nudgeSignal:"Manufacturing consolidation variation surge is active NOW. VIA has no Veeva or Accenture equivalent for CMC post-approval variation management. Freyr Only in this category.", whatThisMeansForFreyr:"VIA is Freyr's uncontested technology right to win at Takeda. No competitor has an equivalent. The only risk is not selling it to the right budget owner — Factory of the Future programme, not CMC Director alone." },
    ],
    nextBestAction:[
      { priority:'WEEK 1-2', action:'Robertson QBR — request and confirm by Week 2', detail:"Contact Robertson immediately to request a strategic account review. Agenda: eCTD v4.0 readiness for H2 2026 launches, freya.intelligence 60-day POC proposal, H2 2026 launch support scope (oveporexton, rusfertide). Reference his NatRevDrugDisc 2025 paper directly in the outreach: 'We read your 2025 paper on cloud-based federated regulatory platforms — Freyr SUBMIT PRO and rDMS are the production-grade operational layer of exactly the architecture you described.'", owner:'Account Lead', urgency:'Immediate' },
      { priority:'WEEK 3-4', action:'Deliver Robertson QBR — ask for Duprey introduction', detail:"Present: (1) SUBMIT PRO eCTD v4.0 deployment scope for oveporexton and rusfertide NDA submissions; (2) freya.intelligence 60-day POC for JP/EU/US launch market regulatory monitoring; (3) VIA ROI model for CMC variation at 25+ manufacturing sites — ask: 'How many FTEs does Takeda spend on variation management?' At the close, ask Robertson: 'Given the Transformation Office is driving the AI investment agenda, would a brief joint session on regulatory automation ROI make sense?' This is the Duprey introduction ask.", owner:'Senior BD + Account Lead', urgency:'Q3 2026' },
      { priority:'WEEK 4-6', action:'Launch freya.intelligence 60-day POC', detail:"Scope the POC to JP/EU/US regulatory monitoring for oveporexton, rusfertide, and zasocitinib pipeline assets. Demonstrate Freya.KnowledgeGraphs competitive intelligence for oveporexton narcolepsy therapeutic area. Deliver weekly intelligence digest — this builds institutional habit and creates tangible ROI evidence for Duprey reporting within the 100-day CEO window.", owner:'Tech Sales + Analytics', urgency:'Q3 2026' },
      { priority:'WEEK 5-7', action:'Duprey first meeting — workforce framing only', detail:"Route via Robertson. Opening: 'How many FTEs does Takeda currently spend on regulatory monitoring and variation management?' Lead with VIA + freya.intelligence FTE reduction model. Do not pitch technology — pitch workforce strategy. Show a practical freya.intelligence demonstration: 'Play with it on your phone.' She learns by doing. Be patient — she thinks in 1-5-10 year transformation horizons, not quarters.", owner:'Senior BD Director', urgency:'Q3 2026' },
      { priority:'WEEK 6-8', action:'SUBMIT PRO deployment scoping on oveporexton NDA', detail:"Follow up QBR with a technical scoping document for SUBMIT PRO deployment on oveporexton NDA/supplement submissions. Robertson's Reg Ops team as the operational contact. Demo to Regulatory Operations Director — this is the tactical technology win that builds the relationship ahead of the freya fusion enterprise conversation.", owner:'Account Lead + Implementation', urgency:'Q3 2026' },
      { priority:'WEEK 7-9', action:'Ricci technical exchange — peer conversation, not demo', detail:"Request 20-minute technical exchange via Duprey or Robertson. Agenda: freya fusion multi-LLM architecture, GxP governance framework mapping to Ricci's 5-pillar responsible AI model (Transparency, Accountability, Robustness, Privacy/Security, Fairness), production deployment evidence from reference client. Not a demo — a peer-to-peer conversation. Do not use the word 'pilot.' Show production-scale deployment, not roadmap.", owner:'Tech Sales + CTO-level Freyr', urgency:'Q3-Q4 2026' },
      { priority:'WEEK 8-10', action:"Identify PV contacts for H2 2026 launch programmes", detail:"Ask Robertson to identify Head of PV and Head of Medical Affairs. 'Who is managing PV for oveporexton and rusfertide?' is the opening question — same single-sentence approach as the Revance PV entry. Three simultaneous commercial launches = three simultaneous PV programme establishment requirements. This is the fastest Growth Services revenue entry in the account.", owner:'Account Lead + PV Team', urgency:'Q3-Q4 2026' },
      { priority:'WEEK 10-12', action:"Prepare CEO Brief for Duprey to deliver to Kim", detail:"Build CEO Brief for Duprey to present to Kim — one page, dual-pressure framing: H2 2026 launch support scope (regulatory operations surge capacity without FTE hiring) and JPY 200B savings contribution from Freyr automation (auditable FTE reduction from VIA + freya.intelligence). Design for Duprey to present, not Freyr. Include reference client outcome with documented numbers.", owner:'Senior BD + Account Lead', urgency:'Q4 2026' },
    ],
    indegenePlays:[ 'SUBMIT PRO · LABEL 360 · rDMS · Regulatory Operations — Q3 2026 URGENT (3 simultaneous launches)', 'VIA · freya.intelligence · Automation ROI model — Q3–Q4 2026 (JPY 200B savings mandate)', 'freya fusion GenAI dossier · freya.docs — Q4 2026–Q1 2027 (Robertson GenAI programme)', 'freya fusion enterprise · VIA · freya.intelligence — FY2027 post-POC (Duprey Transformation mandate)' ],
    pipelineData:[ { quarter:'Q4-2025', value:1.2 }, { quarter:'Q1-2026', value:1.3 }, { quarter:'Q2-2026', value:1.3 }, { quarter:'Q3-2026', value:1.8 } ],
    pipelineNetRenewals:[ { quarter:'Q4-2025', netNew:0.7, renewals:0.5 }, { quarter:'Q1-2026', netNew:0.9, renewals:0.4 }, { quarter:'Q2-2026', netNew:0.9, renewals:0.4 }, { quarter:'Q3-2026', netNew:1.2, renewals:0.6 } ],
    swot:{ S:['Robertson WARM relationship — direct access to regulatory innovation lead','Active Core Services engagement with LABEL 360 and SUBMIT PRO','freya fusion architecture aligns to Robertson\'s published NatRevDrugDisc vision','Global regulatory affiliate network at scale of Takeda operations'], W:['No Transformation Office engagement — Duprey still cold','No CDTO engagement — Ricci cold despite DD&T elevated to CEO-report','Zero technology platform engagement at Takeda','Competitor risk: Accenture/SAP and Veeva approaching Transformation Office'], O:['CEO transition window June–Sept 2026 — 60-90 days to get named in first 100-day review','3 simultaneous H2 2026 launch windows — surge capacity requirement immediate','JPY 200B restructuring mandate creates burning platform for AI-enabled FTE reduction','Robertson willing to introduce to Duprey — one ask away from budget-owner relationship'], T:["Accenture via SAP extension into regulatory process automation — Freyr must be positioned before Transformation Office budget is locked","CEO Kim's first 100-day review will lock technology vendor agenda for FY2027 — window closes Q3 2026","Veeva RIM displacement risk in submission lifecycle management"] },
    revenueTarget:{
      nudgeSignal:"Takeda's projected revenue expansion over FY2026–FY2028 is driven by five primary growth engines: Gastrointestinal (ENTYVIO expansion and subcutaneous adoption), Rare Diseases portfolio growth, Plasma-Derived Therapies capacity expansion, Oncology launches, and Neuroscience pipeline commercialisation. While VYVANSE generic erosion continues to pressure legacy revenue, Takeda's late-stage pipeline and launch portfolio are expected to offset these declines beginning FY2027. Management has identified FY2026–FY2028 as a transition period from patent-cliff recovery to sustainable innovation-led growth.",
      whatThisMeansForFreyr:"The ¥5.0–5.6T revenue trajectory through FY2028 is achievable only if Takeda successfully executes three critical milestones: (1) commercialises late-stage pipeline assets on schedule, (2) continues ENTYVIO global expansion, and (3) accelerates adoption of Plasma-Derived Therapies and Rare Disease products. FY2026–FY2027 launch execution represents the gating event for long-term value creation. Every month of launch delay reduces Takeda's ability to offset VYVANSE revenue pressure.",
      rows:[
        { track:'Gastrointestinal (ENTYVIO Franchise)', fy26h2:'¥1.05T', fy27:'¥1.18T', fy28:'¥1.30T', total:'¥3.53T' },
        { track:'Plasma-Derived Therapies', fy26h2:'¥0.82T', fy27:'¥0.92T', fy28:'¥1.02T', total:'¥2.76T' },
        { track:'Rare Diseases Portfolio', fy26h2:'¥0.60T', fy27:'¥0.70T', fy28:'¥0.82T', total:'¥2.12T' },
        { track:'Oncology', fy26h2:'¥0.45T', fy27:'¥0.58T', fy28:'¥0.75T', total:'¥1.78T' },
        { track:'Neuroscience & New Launches', fy26h2:'¥0.38T', fy27:'¥0.52T', fy28:'¥0.71T', total:'¥1.61T' },
        { track:'TOTAL (Base Case)', fy26h2:'¥3.30T', fy27:'¥3.90T', fy28:'¥4.60T', total:'¥11.80T' },
      ],
      assumptions:[
        "Gastrointestinal (ENTYVIO) growth: global expansion, subcutaneous adoption, and continued market share gains. ENTYVIO remains Takeda's largest growth asset. Assumes continued penetration across inflammatory bowel disease markets, increased subcutaneous formulation adoption, and sustained growth across the US, Europe, and Asia-Pacific. Revenue growth remains above corporate average through FY2028.",
        "Plasma-Derived Therapies: manufacturing expansion and rising immunology demand. Capacity expansion initiatives support increased immunoglobulin and specialty plasma product demand globally, particularly in North America and Europe.",
        "Rare Diseases: continued double-digit growth from hereditary and haematology portfolio. Strong performance from hereditary angioedema, lysosomal storage disorders, and haematology franchises. Growth supported by high retention rates, premium pricing, and limited competitive pressure.",
        "Oncology: pipeline launches and haematologic cancer expansion. Successful commercialisation of late-stage pipeline assets and continued expansion of existing haematology products. Focused on targeted therapies and rare cancers where pricing power is stronger.",
        "Neuroscience: offsetting VYVANSE erosion through new launches. Continued decline in legacy ADHD revenue due to generic competition, offset beginning FY2027 through launch of late-stage neuroscience assets including oveporexton (orexin-based therapy for narcolepsy type 1).",
        "Upper scenario (¥5.6T+) assumes successful commercialisation of three transformative launches by FY2028 — oveporexton, rusfertide, zasocitinib — achieving faster-than-expected neuroscience adoption, expanded oncology penetration globally, and pipeline-driven acceleration beginning FY2027.",
      ],
    },
    playAreas:{
      nudgeSignal:"Takeda's current strategic focus is concentrated around five growth engines: Gastrointestinal Diseases (ENTYVIO franchise), Rare Diseases, Plasma-Derived Therapies, Oncology, and Neuroscience. Despite having one of the strongest specialty-care portfolios in pharma, significant opportunities remain underpenetrated across AI-enabled Regulatory Operations, Global Medical Affairs, Real-World Evidence generation, Digital Health Platforms, and emerging market expansion. The company is actively investing in digital transformation, AI-enabled productivity, and launch readiness for multiple late-stage assets. These initiatives create natural entry points across services, technology, and geographies.",
      whatThisMeansForFreyr:"Technology-led engagement is the lowest-friction path to expanding strategic influence inside Takeda. Every major growth program — ENTYVIO expansion, Rare Disease growth, Plasma-Derived Therapies scaling, and late-stage launch preparation — requires increasing volumes of regulatory intelligence, medical content generation, evidence management, and AI-enabled decision support. The organisations that become embedded in these workflows become strategic long-term partners rather than tactical vendors.",
      coreServices:[
        { service:'Global Regulatory Operations & Launch Excellence', opportunity:"Takeda has multiple high-value launch assets moving through regulatory pathways globally — oveporexton, rusfertide, and zasocitinib. Regulatory publishing, submission management, global variations, labeling coordination, health authority responses, and launch readiness support represent one of the largest service opportunities across the enterprise. SUBMIT PRO eCTD publishing, HA correspondence, country expansion.", revenue:'$12M–18M Annually', priority:'MOST URGENT' },
        { service:'Global Labeling & Lifecycle Management — LABEL 360', opportunity:'Takeda manages hundreds of labels across Gastroenterology, Rare Disease, Oncology, Neuroscience, and Plasma-Derived Therapy portfolios. Label updates driven by safety changes, indication expansions, manufacturing updates, and country-specific requirements create ongoing demand. Three new product labels at launch plus ongoing lifecycle management across 80+ countries.', revenue:'$4M–7M Annually', priority:'HIGH' },
        { service:'Regulatory Intelligence & Competitive Monitoring', opportunity:'Launch planning teams require continuous monitoring of competitors including AbbVie, Johnson & Johnson, Roche, AstraZeneca, Novartis, and Pfizer. freya.intelligence supporting approval pathways, competitor filings, label changes, and market access developments. 60-day POC via Robertson Q3 2026.', revenue:'$3M–5M Annually', priority:'HIGH' },
        { service:'Global Submission Publishing & eCTD v4.0 Operations', opportunity:"eCTD v4.0 readiness is Robertson's stated priority (NatRevDrugDisc 2025). SUBMIT PRO with 800+ validation checks. PMDA Japan eCTD v4.0 mandate effective 2026 directly affects oveporexton Japan NDA. FDA, EMA, PMDA, MHRA, NMPA, Health Canada scope.", revenue:'$5M–8M Annually', priority:'ACTIVE — EXPAND' },
        { service:'Real-World Evidence Regulatory Support', opportunity:"Regulators increasingly require real-world evidence for market access and lifecycle expansion. Takeda's Gastrointestinal and Rare Disease portfolios create strong demand for integrated evidence-generation programmes.", revenue:'$2M–4M Annually', priority:'MEDIUM' },
        { service:'Global Regulatory Strategy Consulting', opportunity:"Complex launch sequencing, indication expansion, accelerated approval pathways, paediatric programmes, and multi-region regulatory planning for late-stage pipeline.", revenue:'$3M–6M Annually', priority:'MEDIUM' },
      ],
      growthServices:[
        { service:'Medical Affairs Operations', opportunity:"Takeda is significantly increasing Medical Affairs activity around late-stage launches. Scientific communications, KOL engagement, publication planning, medical information services, advisory boards, and field medical support all require scale across sleep medicine (oveporexton), haematology (rusfertide), and dermatology (zasocitinib).", revenue:'$10M–15M Annually', priority:'MOST URGENT' },
        { service:'Medical-Legal-Regulatory (MLR) Review', opportunity:"Promotional review activity will accelerate as Takeda prepares multiple launches across sleep medicine, haematology, immunology, and dermatology. Three simultaneous launch cycles. Global MLR workflows remain a major operational burden. Freyr round-the-clock MLR across 120+ countries.", revenue:'$6M–10M Annually', priority:'HIGH' },
        { service:'Pharmacovigilance & Drug Safety', opportunity:"Takeda's growing commercial portfolio requires global pharmacovigilance support including case processing, aggregate reporting, signal detection, risk management plans, literature surveillance, and benefit-risk assessments. Three H2 2026 launches require simultaneous PV programme establishment.", revenue:'$8M–12M Annually', priority:'HIGH' },
        { service:'Evidence Generation & HEOR', opportunity:"Payers increasingly demand outcomes-based evidence. Takeda's Rare Disease and GI portfolios create ongoing requirements for health economics and outcomes research programmes.", revenue:'$4M–7M Annually', priority:'MEDIUM' },
        { service:'Clinical Development Consulting', opportunity:"Support future indications, lifecycle management programmes, protocol optimisation, regulatory strategy, and trial design initiatives across neuroscience and rare disease pipeline.", revenue:'$3M–5M Annually', priority:'FY2027+' },
      ],
      technologyTrack:[
        { platform:'AI Regulatory Intelligence Platform (freya.intelligence)', entryPath:"Takeda's transformation strategy prioritises AI adoption. 60-day POC via Robertson monitoring FDA, EMA, PMDA, MHRA, NMPA, and competitor activity for H2 2026 launch markets. Demonstrate Freya.KnowledgeGraphs for competitive intelligence. Convert to SaaS subscription pre-year-end. $2M–4M ARR potential.", revenue:'$2M–4M ARR', stage:'NEAR-TERM' },
        { platform:'Medical Affairs AI Copilot', entryPath:"AI-powered generation of scientific responses, medical content drafting, literature surveillance, and KOL engagement support. Entry via Head of Medical Affairs alongside MLR and Medical Affairs services conversations.", revenue:'$3M–6M ARR', stage:'Q4 2026' },
        { platform:'Global Regulatory Knowledge Platform (VIA + SUBMIT PRO)', entryPath:"Centralised intelligence for submission planning, variation management, global labeling coordination, and launch readiness. VIA for CMC variation at 25+ manufacturing sites. SUBMIT PRO eCTD v4.0 readiness. Robertson QBR Q3 2026 entry.", revenue:'$2M–5M ARR', stage:'NEAR-TERM' },
        { platform:'Launch Readiness Analytics Platform', entryPath:"Executive dashboards tracking regulatory milestones, payer readiness, KOL engagement, manufacturing readiness, and launch performance. Duprey Transformation Office is the natural home for this investment.", revenue:'$4M–8M ARR', stage:'FY2027' },
        { platform:'AI-Powered Medical Content Generation (freya fusion)', entryPath:"Automated creation and review of scientific content, publications, response documents, training materials, and medical communications. Robertson's GenAI dossier programme (50%+ target) is the exact entry trigger. Multi-LLM architecture aligns with Ricci's 5-pillar framework.", revenue:'$3M–7M ARR', stage:'FY2027' },
        { platform:'Enterprise Regulatory AI Cloud (freya fusion Enterprise)', entryPath:"Unified AI ecosystem supporting Regulatory Affairs, Medical Affairs, Safety, Market Access, and Commercial Operations globally. $10M–20M ARR long-term. Path: freya.intelligence POC → VIA → Medical AI Copilot → freya fusion Enterprise.", revenue:'$10M–20M ARR', stage:'FY2028+' },
      ],
      geographies:[
        { geo:'United States', programme:'Largest commercial market. ENTYVIO expansion, Rare Disease commercialisation, Neuroscience launches (oveporexton), Medical Affairs support, Pharmacovigilance, MLR review, and launch readiness for all three H2 2026 assets.', services:'Regulatory Operations · Medical Affairs · PV · MLR · AI Commercial Analytics', priority:'PRIMARY' },
        { geo:'European Union (EU5 + EEA)', programme:'Critical growth geography for upcoming launches. EMA submissions, HTA requirements, pricing negotiations, labeling coordination, and country-level market access activities create substantial demand. Gap — urgent due to zasocitinib EU preparation.', services:'EMA Regulatory Operations · HTA Support · Regulatory Intelligence · Labeling · Medical Affairs', priority:'GAP — URGENT' },
        { geo:'Japan', programme:"Takeda's home market. PMDA interactions, post-marketing surveillance, medical affairs, and launch activities for oveporexton Japan NDA (eCTD v4.0 mandatory 2026). Freyr Japan affiliate capability.", services:'PMDA Regulatory Operations · Safety · Medical Affairs · Launch Excellence · VIA PMDA', priority:'HIGH' },
        { geo:'China', programme:'Growing strategic importance driven by Rare Disease expansion, Oncology growth, and market access. NMPA filings, local evidence generation, and variation management create sustained demand.', services:'NMPA Regulatory Operations · Regulatory Intelligence · Real-World Evidence · Medical Affairs', priority:'HIGH' },
        { geo:'Emerging Markets (LATAM, Middle East, APAC)', programme:'Future growth driven by expansion of Gastrointestinal, Rare Disease, and Plasma-Derived Therapy portfolios. Country-specific regulatory support and lifecycle management opportunities.', services:'Country Expansion Regulatory Services · Labeling · Safety · Medical Affairs', priority:'MEDIUM' },
      ],
    },
    rightToWin:{
      nudgeSignal:"Takeda's strongest competitive position is not based on scale alone — it is built on a combination of global specialty leadership, deep therapeutic expertise, a rapidly expanding digital-health ecosystem, and one of the industry's most diversified late-stage pipelines. While competitors such as Roche, Pfizer, Novartis, and AstraZeneca possess larger commercial footprints, Takeda maintains advantages in Gastroenterology, Rare Diseases, Plasma-Derived Therapies, and patient-centric market access strategies. Takeda's enterprise-wide AI transformation and digital pipeline initiatives are creating operational advantages across R&D, Medical Affairs, Regulatory Affairs, and Commercial functions.",
      whatThisMeansForFreyr:"Takeda does not need to outspend Big Pharma competitors. It needs to win where specialisation, scientific expertise, patient access, and digital enablement matter most. The companies that pose the greatest threat to Takeda are not necessarily the largest pharmaceutical organisations, but those competing directly in Gastroenterology, Rare Diseases, Plasma-Derived Therapies, Oncology, and AI-enabled commercial execution. Takeda's ability to integrate data, digital technology, real-world evidence, and specialty care delivery creates a defensible competitive moat that becomes increasingly difficult for traditional pharmaceutical competitors to replicate.",
      advantages:[
        { title:'Global Leadership in Gastroenterology (ENTYVIO Franchise)', body:"Takeda owns one of the strongest global inflammatory bowel disease franchises through ENTYVIO. Unlike broad pharmaceutical competitors, Takeda has concentrated expertise in Gastroenterology across clinical development, market access, medical affairs, patient support, and physician engagement. Continued expansion of subcutaneous formulations and global reimbursement coverage strengthens this position. Gastroenterology remains a strategic area where Takeda competes from a position of leadership rather than participation." },
        { title:'Rare Disease Commercial Infrastructure Is Difficult To Replicate', body:"Takeda's Rare Disease business benefits from long-standing physician relationships, specialised patient identification capabilities, genetic testing partnerships, and highly focused field teams. Competitors can launch therapies, but building trusted relationships across rare disease ecosystems often requires years of investment. This creates significant barriers to entry and protects Takeda's market share in multiple orphan indications." },
        { title:'Plasma-Derived Therapies Create Structural Competitive Advantage', body:"Plasma-Derived Therapies require extensive manufacturing infrastructure, plasma collection networks, regulatory approvals, and supply chain capabilities. Unlike small molecule or biologic competitors, new entrants face substantial capital requirements and lengthy timelines. Takeda's existing global plasma network creates a durable competitive advantage that cannot be easily replicated by emerging competitors." },
        { title:'Digital Pipeline And AI Transformation', body:"Takeda has invested heavily in creating a digital pipeline that complements its pharmaceutical pipeline. AI is being deployed across clinical trial optimisation, patient engagement, medical information, manufacturing, predictive analytics, and operational efficiency. Partnerships with technology providers such as Salesforce accelerate Takeda's ability to deploy AI-powered workflows across medical, commercial, and patient-facing functions. This capability increasingly differentiates Takeda from traditional pharmaceutical competitors." },
        { title:'Real-World Data And Evidence Generation Capability', body:"Takeda is increasingly leveraging real-world data to accelerate clinical development, improve trial design, support regulatory submissions, and strengthen payer negotiations. The ability to integrate clinical evidence with real-world outcomes enables faster decision-making and improves commercialisation effectiveness. This capability becomes increasingly valuable as regulators and payers demand evidence beyond traditional clinical trials." },
        { title:'Patient Access And Global Healthcare Partnerships', body:"Takeda's Patient-Trust-Reputation-Business framework supports long-term market access and healthcare system relationships. The company's investments in affordability programs, healthcare partnerships, and access initiatives create differentiation in emerging and developed markets alike. This strengthens physician trust, payer relationships, and patient retention." },
      ],
      whyWeWin:[
        { title:'Specialty Over Scale', body:'Takeda focuses resources in areas where scientific expertise matters more than sheer commercial size.' },
        { title:'High-Barrier Therapeutic Areas', body:'Rare diseases and plasma-derived therapies create natural protection from competitive disruption.' },
        { title:'Digital-Enabled Operating Model', body:"The company's digital pipeline strategy is improving speed, efficiency, and decision quality across the organisation." },
        { title:'Patient-Centric Differentiation', body:"Takeda's access, support, and healthcare partnership strategy strengthens long-term stakeholder trust." },
        { title:'Diversified Growth Engines', body:'Revenue growth is supported by multiple therapeutic areas rather than dependence on a single blockbuster asset.' },
      ],
      competitiveGrid:[
        { area:'Gastroenterology (IBD)', freyr:'Leader', iconParexel:'Limited', veeva:'Limited', other:'Present' },
